[2] Malaysia
Date: 28 Dec 2015
Source: Rakyat Post [edited]
http://www.therakyatpost.com/news/2015/12/28/health-ministry-to-provide-measles-vaccination-for-babies-as-early-as-nine-months/


Health Ministry to provide measles vaccinations for babies as young as 9 months
-------------------------
Health director-general Datuk Dr Noor Hisham Abdullah states that 2 children died due to measles in 2015, compared with 1 death during 2014.

Babies as young as 9 months old will be vaccinated for measles beginning in April 2016 based on the increasing number of measles-related cases in the country.

According to a report by New Straits Times today, Health deputy director-general (Public Health) Datuk Dr Lokman Hakim Sulaiman said that early vaccination was timely and necessary considering the increase in the number of measles cases in the past 3 years.

"Health Ministry will bring forward the 1st dose of measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccination to 9 months and 2nd dose to 12 months, from the current 12 months and 7 years.

"It is timely and necessary as measles is still endemic in Malaysia, indicated by the increase in the number of cases and clusters in the past 3 years. Beginning [in 2016], babies in the peninsula and Sarawak will get their 1st MMR shot at 9 months, and the 2nd dose at 12 months," he was quoted as saying in the report.

Dr Lokman further said that babies in Sabah would continue to receive measles vaccination at 6 months and would receive their 1st MMR dose at 9 months and the 2nd was when they reached 12 months.

He added that the new schedule would start with babies born on 1 Jul 2016 onwards.

Other than that, Dr Lokman said that they would carry out campaigns to inform the public about the new schedule aside from giving them the awareness about the health issue.

"This would provide sufficient time for medical personnel to inform parents on the new schedule, set new appointments for MMR shots and acquire a sufficient supply of vaccines. We will also carry out campaigns on the new vaccination schedule to create awareness and educate the public. This has been discussed with the ministry's Family Health Development Division and state health personnel," he said.

In the report Dr Lokman also said that immunising infants before the age of 6 months often failed to induce seroconversion due to the immaturity of the immune system and the presence of neutralising maternal antibodies. Seroconversion is the time period during which a specific antibody develops and becomes detectable in the blood.

Measles is a virus that lives in the nose and throat mucus of an infected person. It develops into a highly infectious disease that occurs only in humans.

According to the report, it said that the number of measles cases in the country had tripled as of September 2015.

"Health Ministry statistics revealed that the number of confirmed measles cases rose to 794 cases (34.7 per million population -- annualised) from 235 cases (7.8 per million population) in 2014 and 195 cases (6.6 per million population) in 2013," it read.

It is also reported that the Health director-general Datuk Dr Noor Hisham Abdullah stating that 2 children died of measles in 2015, compared with 1 death during 2014. Most cases of measles struck infants and children aged 6 years and below.

"The number of outbreaks increased more than threefold, with 37 episodes from only 11 last year, with cases had been reported in childcare institutions, schools and detention centres," said Dr Hisham as quoted in the report.

